gomodel:SYNGO_3800  a     owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Automated change 2026-01-08: GO:0140232 replaced by GO:0005222" , "Rationale: Fig.5: \"HCN1 channels inhibit mEPSC frequency by limiting T-type Ca2+ channel activity\"\n[Fig.6: \"Co-localisation of HCN1 and CaV3.2 subunits on EC synaptic terminals\"]\nFig.7: \"Hyperpolarization enhances pre-synaptic T-type Ca2+ channel activation\"\n\n- regulation of presynaptic membrane potiential\n\nliteral: \"The significant findings of this study are that functional HCN1 channels are present on glutamatergic synaptic terminals synapsing onto EC layer III neurons where they reduce spontaneous and evoked neurotransmitter release. These effects are at least partly due to altered availability of low-threshold, voltage-gated T-type Ca2+ channel. In support, electron microscopy showed that HCN1 and CaV3.2 subunits co-exist on EC pre-synaptic terminals...Remarkably, our results suggest that the presence of pre-synaptic HCN channels depolarizes the RMP, thereby restricting Ca2+ entry via pre-synaptic T-type Ca2+ channel activity and preventing glutamate release (Figs 44 -7). This suggests that pre-synaptic HCN channels may provide an additional regulatory mechanism for controlling synaptic release at these synapses.\". Experimental description: \"\nHCN146 and CaV3.242 heterozygote breeding pairs were used to generate HCN1 null (HCN1-/-), CaV3.2 null (CaV3.2-/-) and wildtype littermates as described in Huang et al. (2009)4. All electrophysiological experiments involving transgenic mice were done blindly. \"" ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2514-0216" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0003-0593-3443" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2286-1587" ;
        dc:date           "2026-01-08" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_MF_3800" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10090" .

